<subSubSection id="C337088DF77DB13CB182FF2030CD41EB" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8B925B06F77DB13CB182FF2031B941C7" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">
<collectionCode id="ED3CC3C3F77DB13CB182FF2032C243B4" box="[199,251,223,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">TYPE</collectionCode>
MATERIAL: From Sundevall’s description (1850: 110) it appears that his new name is based on, firstly, the description of a single specimen by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F77DB13CB36CFEFC30CB425F" author="Kaup, J. J." box="[553,754,259,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" pagination="325 - 386" refId="ref28962" refString="Kaup, J. J. (1847) Monographien der Genera der Falconidae. Isis von Oken, Leipzig, 1 - 5, 39 - 80, 83 - 121, 161 - 212, 241 - 283, 325 - 386. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 155025" type="journal article" year="1847">Kaup (1847: 344)</bibRefCitation>
, and secondly, by at least 
<specimenCount id="9D2B908FF77DB13CB550FEFC3645425F" box="[1045,1148,259,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="adult">one adult</specimenCount>
male and a young female collected by Wahlberg. This is confirmed by Sundevall’s acquisition catalogue, according to which there seems to have been only a male and a female from Durban available. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F77DB13CB273FEB436714227" author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[822,1096,331,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref28755" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1926) Types of birds in the Royal Natural History Museum in Stockholm. Arkiv f or Zoologi, 19, 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="1926">Gyldenstolpe (1926: 91)</bibRefCitation>
refers to NRM 569845 [7571] as a “type”, which we treat here as a 
<typeStatus id="5496E5A4F77DB13CB375FE9030AE42CB" box="[560,663,367,393]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation of this adult male collected 
<date id="FF937DC6F77DB13CB51DFE90372742CB" box="[1112,1310,367,393]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" value="1841-02-27">
27 February 
<quantity id="4CD5F6E3F77DB13CB5A3FE90372742CB" box="[1254,1310,367,393]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.67614" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" unit="in" value="1841.0">1841</quantity>
</date>
in Durban. The 
<specimenCount id="9D2B908FF77DB13CB18EFE6C33A642EF" box="[203,415,403,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="generic" typeStatus="paralectotypes">two paralectotypes</specimenCount>
are: NRM 538380 [7572], a mounted juvenile female collected 
<date id="FF937DC6F77DB13CB5C4FE6C372F42EF" box="[1153,1302,403,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" value="1840-04-07">
7 April 
<quantity id="4CD5F6E3F77DB13CB59BFE6C372F42EF" box="[1246,1302,403,429]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6736" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" unit="in" value="1840.0">1840</quantity>
</date>
in Durban; and Kaup’s specimen, now evidently missing. There is no known geographical origin of the missing Kaup specimen. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC26F7F77DB13CB190FE24335A42B7" author="Kaup, J. J." box="[213,355,475,501]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" pagination="325 - 386" refId="ref28962" refString="Kaup, J. J. (1847) Monographien der Genera der Falconidae. Isis von Oken, Leipzig, 1 - 5, 39 - 80, 83 - 121, 161 - 212, 241 - 283, 325 - 386. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 155025" type="journal article" year="1847">Kaup (1847)</bibRefCitation>
states “this bird came as 
<specimenCount id="9D2B908FF77DB13CB33AFE24312142B7" box="[639,792,475,501]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
to London and was sold to a German, either a scientist or a dealer” [translation by Jörn Köhler]. During the period when Johann Jakob Kaup prepared his text on the genera of raptors, he was associated with the collection in Darmstadt (HLMD). It is uncertain if this specimen was ever in the Darmstadt collection, and there is no such specimen there today (Jörn Köhler, HLMD, in litt.). Although we have been unable to trace the Kaup specimen, it is not known to be lost.
</paragraph>
